column11: For the purposes of this question, the EU Delegation to Libya will count. The EU is actively monitoring the Libyan security situation and some countries are considering opening their embassies (Euractiv, European External Action Service, Press TV, CNN). Confused? Given the occasional outbreaks of militia violence there and the unsettled security conditions, EU countries are only gradually starting to reopen in Tripoli. The Dutch and Italians reopened embassies in 2017; an outbreak of fresh violence in January 2018 may have caused other EU members to hesitate. I think it likely the Germans, French, and British will come back next. But maybe not all three by by 1 June. Then it takes time to locate office space and housing, rebuild facilities, etc.

Since my last forecast on 24 Jan, Libya has been in a "more of the same" pattern. Still vague talk about proceeding to elections, and a voter registration effort has been completed ... of uncertain effectiveness. So the largest influence on my changed forecast is that we are running out of time to see "major progress" of the kind that would be quite likely to trigger European nations to re-open their embassies.

Seeing as February is coming to a close, EU nations are running out of time to reopen their embassies in the war-torn Libya before this window of June 2018 expires. While representatives from Libya continue to urge EU nations to reinvest their diplomatic efforts in the country, there has been no talk or progress made in regarding the reopening of an EU embassy in Libya. Until European officials begin to discuss this possibility, I will remain skeptical that no embassy shall be opened before June.

There seem to be two considerations regarding re-opening embassies in Libya. The first is the straight forward question of it being safe for the diplomats, the second is does any authority exist in the specific location where the embassy is, that can be considered to be the legitimate and de facto government of Libya. Legally an embassy is to some specific authority. It seems to me that in practice it is not clear what the authority in Libya is - The GNA is recognised as the authority and they do more or less control Tripoli, but not securely and the GNA does not control the majority of the country. Because Libya is a divided country most problems that diplomats are trying to address require negotiations with and between different factions that control different areas of the country and do not trust each other, and therefore need to take place on neutral ground, which means somewhere outside Libya. Therefore although Libya has a lot of problems that foreign governments would like solved, it is not immediately obvious that this can be done better by an embassy within Libya than one in Tunis. Having said that, Italy re-opened its embassy in Tripoli some months ago. It is reported that France has irritated Italy by hosting talks between the two rival Libyan governments, but France has suggested that Italy had been wrong to back a Misrata based militia. I would suggest that having an embassy within Libya, which means working with who ever controls the territory in which you are based, creates an obvious impression that your country supports one faction over the others, which may not be helpful. Therefore I suggest that most western countries might see getting agreement for a single Libyan government needs to come before re-opening embassies. However if one moves they will probably all move.
